{{for|the violinist|Dong-Suk Kang}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}} {{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = | name = Kang Dong-suk | other_names = Donald Kang | honorific_suffix = | image = Donald Kang.jpg | alt = | image_size = | caption = Kang in 2014 | birth_name = Kang Dong-suk | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1969|5|25}} | birth_place = [[Hapcheon]], South Korea | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = Yachtsman | known_for = First Korean to complete a solo [[circumnavigation]] of the [[globe]] in a [[yacht]] | title = | children = | spouse = | salary = | networth = | website = {{URL | donaldkang.com}} | module = {{Infobox Korean name|child=yes | hangul = 강동석 | hanja = 姜東錫 | rr = Gang Dongseok | mr = Kang Tongsŏk}} }}
'''Kang Dong-suk''' ({{ko-hhrm|강동석}}; born May 25, 1969; {{a.k.a.}} Donald Kang) is a [[yachtsman]] and [[adventurer]] from South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kahistorymuseum.org/%EA%B0%95-%EB%8F%99-%EC%84%9D-donald-s-kang-%E5%A7%9C%E6%9D%B1%E9%8C%AB/| title=강동석 Donald S Kang 姜東錫|accessdate=2017-08-05|work=Korean American History Museum|date=2014-07-07| language=Korean}}</ref>
On June 8, 1997, he became the first Korean to sail around the world single-handedly, when he completed a [[circumnavigation]] on a 30-foot (9.2-meter) [[sailboat]] ''Pioneer 2'' (선구자 2), covering over 70,000 kilometers in 3 years and 5 months.<ref name="Donga1">{{cite news|last=Jun|first=Chang|title=[스포츠종합] 강동석, 41개월간 한국인 최초 '단독 요트 세계일주'|trans-title=Sports News - First Korean solo-Circumnavigator Kang Dong-suk sailing for 41 months|url=http://news.donga.com/3/all/20041130/8134012/1|accessdate=2017-08-05|work=[[The Dong-a Ilbo]]|date=2004-11-30| language=Korean|location=Seoul}}</ref><ref name="Hankook">{{cite news|last=Lee|first=Chang-Ho|title=People 강동석 - 내 인생의 8할은 도전과 모험이었이었다|trans-title=My Life was mostly Challenges and Adventures|url=http://sports.hankooki.com/lpage/people/201012/sp20101217170132106610.htm|work=Sports [[Hankook Ilbo]] Daily|date=2010-12-17|accessdate=2017-08-05|language=Korean|location=Seoul}}</ref> In 1991, he completed the first [[single-handed sailing]] voyage of the [[Pacific]] by a Korean in his first sailboat ''Pioneer 1'' (선구자 1), a 29-foot (8.7-meter) boat, travelling the distance of 11,700 kilometers in 7 months. After arriving in Korea, he donated the Pioneer 1 to the [[Korea Naval Academy]].<ref name="Hankook" />
[[File:Pioneer 2 route1.jpg|thumb|300px|Circumnavigation route of ''Pioneer 2'']]
The [[Republic of Korea Navy]], in recognition of Kang's sailing achievements, awarded him the first ever Honorary Member of the Republic of Korea Navy (명예해군) title.<ref name="SBS2">{{cite news|last=Song|first=Sung-Joon|title=명예해군의 결혼|trans-title=Hononary Navy's Wedding|url=http://news.sbs.co.kr/news/endPage.do?news_id=N0311767656|accessdate=2017-08-05|work=[[Seoul Broadcasting System]] Nightly 8 o'clock News|date=2005-06-19|location=Seoul| language=Korean}}</ref> In November 1997, following his return from the sailing solo-circumnavigation, South Korean President [[Kim Young-sam]] invited Kang to the [[Blue House]] and awarded him the "New Korean" (신한국인) title.<ref name="MBC">{{cite news|last=Lee|first=In Yong|title=김영삼대통령,'신한국인' 초청 오찬|trans-title=South Korean President Kim Young-Sam meets "New Korean" Awardees at Blue House|url=http://imnews.imbc.com/20dbnews/history/1997/1770968_19482.html|accessdate=2017-08-08|work=[[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation]] Nightly News at 9 o'clock|date=1997-11-13| language=Korean|location=Seoul}}</ref>
In 1999, as a member of a Korean climbing team, he attempted to summit [[Broad Peak]] in the [[Himalayas]], the 12th highest mountain in the world.<ref name="EconomicDaily">{{cite news|last=Ahn| first=Hyun-Duk|title=요트 세계일주 20년 맞은 강동석씨 "도전은 최고 스펙이자 삶의 밑거름"|trans-title=On 20th Anniversary of Solo-Circumnavigation, Kang on Life Lessons and Challenges|url=http://www.sedaily.com/NewsView/1OG4IXJCBV|accessdate=2017-08-05|work=[[Hankook Ilbo Media Group|Seoul Economic Daily]]|date=2017-05-30| language=Korean|location=Seoul}}</ref> The team had to turn back when a climbing member fell to his death.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jun|first=Jong-ju|title=연세산악회 99 브로드피크 원정대|trans-title=Yonsei University Alpine Club Broad Peak Expedition|url=http://www.mountainkorea.com/contents_view.html?contentsid=329&menuid=&submenuid=|work=Mountain Korea Magazine|accessdate=2017-08-24|language=Korean|location=Seoul}}</ref> In 2005, Kang served as the expedition manager for the Korean mountaineer [[Park Young-seok]]'s [[North Pole]] expedition, supporting Park achieve an [[Explorers Grand Slam]].<ref name="Munwha">{{cite news|last=Yang|first= Sung-wook|title=이번엔 북극점··· 1% 가능성만 있어도 도전|trans-title=This time to the North Pole, even if There is 1% of Possibility|url=http://www.munhwa.com/news/view.html?no=20050110010129141230140|accessdate=2017-08-23|work=[[Munhwa Ilbo]]|date=2005-01-10| language=Korean|location=Seoul}}</ref> Park became the first person to climb all 14 [[Eight-thousander]]s and achieve the Explorers Grand Slam.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.everestnews.com/stories2005/park05012005.htm |accessdate=2017-08-05|website=EverestNews.com|date=2005-05-01 |title= Mr. Park completes the Grand Slam}}</ref>
Kang chronicled his sailing adventures in his book ''Yes I am passionate about the sea''. He also gives frequent lectures about his experience and expeditions.<ref name="EconomicDaily" /> Sailboats (Pioneers 1 and 2) used by Kang for his sailing voyages are on display at the Korea Naval Academy and the [[Korea National Maritime Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|title=선구자Ⅱ호|trans-title=PioneerⅡ| url=https://www.knmm.or.kr/Menu04_Relic/relic_01_view.aspx?str1=all&str2=%EC%84%A0%EA%B5%AC%EC%9E%90&x=0&y=0&str5=&fld_seq=295|accessdate=2017-08-05|work=[[Korea National Maritime Museum]]|date=2011-12-16| language=Korean}}</ref>
[[File:Pioneer 2 that sailed around the world.jpg|thumb|upright|''Pioneer 2'' on display at the [[Korea National Maritime Museum]]]] [[File:Pioneer 1 that sailed the Pacific.jpg|thumb|''Pioneer 1'' on display at the [[Korea Naval Academy]]]]
