'''''Kaya''''' (plural ''makaya'' or kayas) is a [[sacred grove|sacred forest]] of the [[Mijikenda peoples|Mijikenda people]] in the former [[Coast Province]] of [[Kenya]]. The ''kaya'' forest is considered to be an intrinsic source of ritual power and the origin of cultural identity;{{sfn|Parkin|2006|p=37}} it is also a place of prayer for members of the particular ethnic group.<ref name=Nyamweru1996>{{cite journal|last=Nyamweru|first=Celia|title=Sacred Groves Threatened by Development: The Kaya Forests of Kenya|journal=Cultural Survival Quarterly|date=Fall 1996|volume=20|series="Who's Local Here?" Politics of Participation in Development|issue=3|url=http://www.culturalsurvival.org/ourpublications/csq/article/sacred-groves-threatened-development-the-kaya-forests-kenya|accessdate=14 December 2013}}</ref> The settlement, ritual centre, and fortified enclosure associated with the forest are also part of the ''kaya''. In the present day, the ''kaya'' is also referred to as a traditional organizational unit of the Mijikenda.<ref name=Buluma2013>{{cite news|last=Buluma|first=Rodgers|title=The elderly targeted for murder|url=http://m.news24.com/kenya/MyNews24/Elderly-people-being-victimized-in-Kilifi-20130702|accessdate=15 December 2013|newspaper=[[News24]]|date=July 2, 2013}}</ref> Eleven of the approximately 30 separate ''kaya'' have been grouped together and inscribed as the Sacred Mijikenda Kaya Forests, a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]].

==Geography==
More than 50 ''kaya'' have been identified within the [[Kwale County|Kwale]], [[Mombasa County|Mombasa]], and [[Kilifi County|Kilifi]] counties.<ref name=unescoNOMINATION>{{cite web|title=NOMINATION DOSSIER FOR INSCRIPTION ON THE WORLD HERITAGE LIST THE SACRED MIJIKENDA KAYA FORESTS|url=http://whc.unesco.org/uploads/nominations/1231rev.pdf|publisher=UNESCO|accessdate=15 December 2013|page=10|date=January 2008}}</ref>  They measure between 30 and 300 hectares each.<ref name=africanworldheritagesites.org>{{cite web|title=Sacred Mijikenda Kaya Forests - Kenya|url=http://www.africanworldheritagesites.org/cultural-places/traditional-cultural-landscapes/kaya-forests.html|publisher=African World Heritage|accessdate=14 December 2013}}</ref> These are scattered over a coastal stretch of {{convert|200|km}}<ref name=Unesco/> in the southern coastal plains area of Kenya, between the towns of [[Mombasa]] and [[Kilifi]].<ref name=World>{{Cite web|url=http://www.africanworldheritagesites.org/cultural-places/traditional-cultural-landscapes/kaya-forests.html|title= Sacred Mijikenda Kaya Forests – Kenya|accessdate=15 December 2013|publisher= African World Heritage}}</ref> While visitors are not allowed to enter most ''makaya'', Kaya Kinondo, a 30-hectare forest on [[Diani Beach]], allows visitors and falls under the auspices of the Kaya Kinondo Ecotourism Project.<ref name=ecotourismkenya.org>{{cite web|title=Kaya Kinondo Ecotourism Project|url=http://www.ecotourismkenya.org/viewcommunity.php?cid=77|publisher=Eco Tourism Kenya|accessdate=14 December 2013}}</ref>

==History==
Many ''kaya'' were originally fortified villages of the various ethnic groups, the [[Digo people|Digo]], [[Chonyi]], [[Kambe]], [[Duruma]], [[Kauma]], [[Ribe (ethnic group)|Ribe]], [[Rabai]], [[Jibana]], and [[Giriama]] people. The villages have lowland tropical forest areas in their surrounds and were reached via paths through the forest. The forest flora was used solely for the collection of medicinal herbs. The practices of tree cutting, livestock grazing, and farmland clearing were not permitted within a ''kaya''.<ref name=Nyamweru1996 />

In the present day, intensive deforestation for agricultural use and logging necessitated declaring 38 ''kaya'' forest areas legally as national monuments. Local communities manage these areas.{{sfn|Zeppel|2006|p=136}}

==Wildlife and conservation==
Wildlife in the Kaya Kinodao area has been identified which can be visited as part of ecotourism project. While plant species identified are 187 plant, bird species are 48, and butterflies 45 species.[[Colobus monkey]] and [[Golden-rumped elephant shrew]] are also reported.{{sfn|Zeppel|2006|p=136}}

Entry into the forest was dictated by the traditional rules set by a governing body called the ''ngambi'' formed by elderly members of the community. This governing body was primarily concerned with its management, conservation and utilization of the biological resources in adherence to the traditional beliefs about the sacredness of the forest. However, the creation of central governing body has affected the role of the local elders.{{sfn|Trosper|2011|p=58}}

An Eco Tourism project was launched in 2001 with funds provided by [[Ford Foundation]] with the objective of generating income for the local people and also encourage ecotorism and concurrently help preserve the sacredness of the forests.{{sfn|Zeppel|2006|p=136}}  Eleven Mijikenda ''kaya'' were grouped together and inscribed as the Sacred Mijikenda Kaya Forests, a World Heritage Site, in 2008 under criteria (iii), (v), and (vi).<ref name=Unesco>{{cite web|title=Sacred Mijikenda Kaya Forests|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1231|publisher=UNESCO|accessdate=14 December 2013}}</ref>

==Culture==
[[Fingo (talisman)|''Fingo'']] (protective talismans) are buried in the ''kaya'' and are cared for by ''kaya'' elders who protect the traditions of the Mijikenda.{{sfn|Njogu|Middleton|2009|pp=296-297}} Mijikenda believe that they brought the ''fingo'' charms from their ancestral home of [[Shungwaya]], a [[myth of origin]]. In the present day, many ''fingo'' are lost or stolen, considered to be [[objet d'art]].{{sfn|Trillo|2013|p=551}}

There are many myths and beliefs narrated by the local women of the area which relate to the sacredness of these forests. It is the general belief that the forests are inhabited by [[spirits]]. Some of them believe that cutting a tree with a [[machete]] could result in the machete rebounding and causing injury to the leg which could be healed only by offering cloth to village elders in a ceremony. It is also believed that food cooked using wood from these sacred forest could cause sickness, and also that a dwelling built with timber drawn from the forest would collapse. The conservation of  the sacredness of the forest was aimed at preserving its darkness.{{sfn|Eaton|Lorentzen|2004|p=48}}

