{{other uses}}
'''Shala''' was an ancient [[Sumer]]ian goddess of grain and the emotion of compassion. The symbols of grain and compassion combine to reflect the importance of agriculture in the [[Sumerian mythology|mythology of Sumer]], and the belief that an abundant harvest was an act of compassion from the deities.<ref name="Farrar">{{cite book |author=Stewart and Janet Farrar|title=''The Witches' Goddess: The Feminine Principle of Divinity''|publisher=Phoenix Publishing|year=1987|ISBN=978-0919345911|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=42EOOAAACAAJ&dq=The+Witches%27+Goddess:+The+Feminine+Principle+of+Divinity+1987&hl=en&sa=X&ei=AmmgVPHvIsmy7Qae6oD4Dg&ved=0CCAQ6AEwAA}}</ref> Traditions identify Shala as wife of the fertility god [[Dagon]], or consort of the storm god [[Hadad]]' also called Ishkur.<ref name="Symbols">{{cite book|author=Jeremy Black and Anthony Green|title=''Gods, Demons and Symbols of Ancient Mesopotamia''|publisher=University of Texas Press|year=1992|ISBN=978-0-292-70794-8|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=pr8-i1iFnIQC&dq=Gods,+Demons+and+Symbols+of+Ancient+Mesopotamia&hl=en&sa=X&ei=RGugVJIhiJTtBritgNAO&ved=0CCcQ6AEwAQ|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150103022312/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=pr8-i1iFnIQC&dq=Gods,+Demons+and+Symbols+of+Ancient+Mesopotamia&hl=en&sa=X&ei=RGugVJIhiJTtBritgNAO&ved=0CCcQ6AEwAQ|archivedate=2015-01-03|df=}}</ref> In ancient depictions, she carries a double-headed mace or scimitar embellished with lion heads.<ref name="Jordan">{{cite book |author=Michael Jordan|title=''Encyclopedia of Gods''|publisher=Kyle Cathie Limited|year=2002|ISBN=978-1-85626-131-9|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ftUENQAACAAJ&dq=Michael+Jordan,+Encyclopedia+of+Gods+2002&hl=en&sa=X&ei=rmugVLWHAsGf7gaotYGwDg&ved=0CCAQ6AEwAA}}</ref> Sometimes she is depicted as being borne atop one or two lionesses. From very early times, she is associated with the constellation [[Virgo (constellation)|Virgo]] and vestiges of symbolism associated with her have persisted in representations of the constellation to current times, such as the ear of grain, even as the deity name changed from culture to culture.
The Shala Mons, a [[List of montes on Venus|mountain on Venus]], is named after her.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shala Mons|url=http://planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov/Feature/5459?__fsk=1374708739|website=Gazetteer of Planetary Nomenclature}}</ref>
